# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: power-analysis-vlsi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] In computer architecture, **clock gating** is a popular power management technique used in many synchronous circuits for reducing dynamic power dissipation (a significant source of power dissipation in digital designs), by removing the clock signal when the circuit, or a subpart of it, is idle.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Clock gating saves power by pruning part of the clock tree distribution, at the cost of adding more logic to a circuit.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Pruning the clock turns off portions of the circuitry so that the flip-flops in them do not switch state, as switching the state consumes power.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] When not switched, the switching power consumption is reduced.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] This technique is particularly effective in systems with significant idle time or predictable periods of inactivity within specific modules.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Digital circuits consume power through multiple mechanisms, typically categorised into dynamic and static components.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] These components collectively define the total power profile of a digital system, and their optimisation is crucial for low-power design.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] These components become increasingly critical in modern integrated circuits, especially with technology scaling, where leakage and short-circuit power can constitute a significant portion of the total power budget.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Clock gating is one of several techniques used to reduce the power consumption of digital circuits.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] It specifically targets the dynamic power component, Pdynamic, by lowering unnecessary switching activity in clock signals.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] By turning off the clock signal to portions of the circuit when not in use, clock gating reduces *α*, thus decreasing overall dynamic power consumption.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] This differs from the power-gating technique, which cuts the power supply entirely and simultaneously reduces multiple sources of power dissipation.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Clock-gating techniques typically operate by targeting specific clock regions.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] To apply these techniques, it is often necessary to modify the registers/(flip-flops) in the circuit so that they can be controlled and disconnected from the clock distribution network, effectively isolating blocks of combinational logic.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] External circuits can control clock and activation signals through a technique known as Enabled Flip-Flops, or they can be generated internally using traditional clock-gating methods.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] When the control signal (CNTRL) is set to 1, the clock-gating circuit turns off the clock by holding it at a fixed logic level, either 0 or 1.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] One typical implementation uses a CMOS pass-transistor controlled by the inverted control signal.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] It can be inserted into the design manually by the RTL designers (typically as module-level clock gating) by instantiating library-specific integrated clock gating (ICG) cells to gate the clocks of specific modules or registers.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] It can be semi-automatically inserted into the RTL by automated clock-gating tools.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] These tools either insert ICG cells into the RTL or add enable conditions into the RTL code.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] These typically also offer sequential clock-gating optimisations.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] A common implementation of clock gating uses a level-sensitive latch (or flip-flop) to prevent glitches on the gated clock.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] The enable signal is captured only when the clock is in its inactive phase, ensuring that the gating control remains stable during the active clock transition.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] This avoids short unwanted pulses (glitches) that can cause incorrect switching in sequential elements.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Many integrated clock-gating (ICG) cells include this latch internally to provide a glitch-free gated clock.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] In general, clock gating applied at a coarser granularity leads to reduced resource overhead and greater power savings.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Any RTL modifications to improve clock gating will result in functional changes to the design (since the registers will now hold different values), which need to be verified.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Sequential clock gating is the process of propagating enable conditions through upstream and downstream sequential elements, allowing additional registers to be clock-gated.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] This technique extends clock gating beyond individual flip-flops to optimise power savings across larger circuit portions.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Chips designed for battery-powered or ultra-low-power applications—such as mobile phones, wearable devices, and embedded systems—typically simultaneously implement multiple clock gating strategies.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Manual clock gating involves software drivers that enable or disable clocks to various idle controllers.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] In contrast, automatic clock gating uses hardware mechanisms to detect when a clock is unnecessary and dynamically turns it off.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] These approaches often operate together within the same enable tree.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] For example, an internal bus or bridge may employ automatic gating, keeping the clock disabled until accessed by the CPU or a DMA engine.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] In contrast, peripherals on that bus might be permanently gated off if unused in a particular board design.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] Clock gating may also be used to reduce area.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/clock-gating] If many registers have the same enable, clock gating them at a higher point in the clock tree may cost only one integrated clock gate worth of area, but would save a 2:1 multiplexer (the "feedback mux" normally used to implement the enable) worth of area per register that has that enable.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] Designing CPUs that perform tasks efficiently without overheating is a major consideration of nearly all CPU manufacturers to date.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] Historically, early CPUs implemented with vacuum tubes consumed power on the order of many kilowatts.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] Current CPUs in general-purpose personal computers, such as desktops and laptops, consume power in the order of tens to hundreds of watts.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] Some other CPU implementations use very little power; for example, the CPUs in mobile phones often use just a few watts of electricity, while some microcontrollers used in embedded systems may consume only a few milliwatts or even as little as a few microwatts.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] For example, the Pentium 4 2.8 GHz has a 68.4 W typical thermal power and 85 W maximum thermal power.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] When the CPU is idle, it will draw far less than the typical thermal power.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] Datasheets normally contain the thermal design power (TDP), which is the maximum amount of heat generated by the CPU, which the cooling system in a computer is required to dissipate.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] Both Intel and Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) have defined TDP as the maximum heat generation for thermally significant periods, while running worst-case non-synthetic workloads; thus, TDP is not reflecting the actual maximum power of the processor.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] This ensures the computer will be able to handle essentially all applications without exceeding its thermal envelope, or requiring a cooling system for the maximum theoretical power (which would cost more but in favor of extra headroom for processing power).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] In many applications, the CPU and other components are idle much of the time, so idle power contributes significantly to overall system power usage.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] When the CPU uses power management features to reduce energy use, other components, such as the motherboard and chipset, take up a larger proportion of the computer's energy.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] In applications where the computer is often heavily loaded, such as scientific computing, performance per watt (how much computing the CPU does per unit of energy) becomes more significant.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] CPUs typically use a significant portion of the power consumed by the computer.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] Other major uses include fast video cards, which contain graphics processing units, and power supplies.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] In laptops, the LCD's backlight also uses a significant portion of overall power.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] While energy-saving features have been instituted in personal computers for when they are idle, the overall consumption of today's high-performance CPUs is considerable.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/cpu-power-dissipation] This is in strong contrast with the much lower energy consumption of CPUs designed for low-power devices.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] In computer architecture, **dynamic voltage scaling** is a power management technique in which the voltage used in a component is increased or decreased, depending upon circumstances.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Dynamic voltage scaling to increase voltage is known as **overvolting**; dynamic voltage scaling to decrease voltage is known as **undervolting**.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Undervolting is done in order to conserve power, particularly in laptops and other mobile devices, where energy comes from a battery and thus is limited, or in rare cases, to increase reliability.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Overvolting is done in order to support higher frequencies for performance.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The term "overvolting" is also used to refer to increasing static operating voltage of computer components to allow operation at higher speed (overclocking).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] MOSFET-based digital circuits operate using voltages at circuit nodes to represent logical state.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The voltage at these nodes switches between a high voltage and a low voltage during normal operation—when the inputs to a logic gate transition, the transistors making up that gate may toggle the gate's output.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Toggling a MOSFET's state requires changing its gate voltage from below the transistor's threshold voltage to above it (or from above it to below it).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] However, changing the gate's voltage requires charging or discharging the capacitance at its node.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] This capacitance is the sum of capacitances from various sources: primarily transistor gate capacitance, diffusion capacitance, and wires (coupling capacitance).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Higher supply voltages result in faster slew rate (rate of change of voltage per unit of time) when charging and discharging, which allows for quicker transitioning through the MOSFET's threshold voltage.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Additionally, the more the gate voltage exceeds the threshold voltage, the lower the resistance of the transistor's conducting channel.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] This results in a lower RC time constant for quicker charging and discharging of the capacitance of the subsequent logic stage.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Quicker transitioning afforded by higher supply voltages allows for operating at higher frequencies.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Many modern components allow voltage regulation to be controlled through software (for example, through the BIOS).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] It is usually possible to control the voltages supplied to the CPU, RAM, PCI, and PCI Express (or AGP) port through a PC's BIOS.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] However, some components do not allow software control of supply voltages, and hardware modification is required by overclockers seeking to overvolt the component for extreme overclocks.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Video cards and motherboard northbridges are components which frequently require hardware modifications to change supply voltages.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] These modifications are known as "voltage mods" or "Vmod" in the overclocking community.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Undervolting is reducing the voltage of a component, usually the processor, reducing temperature and cooling requirements, and possibly allowing a fan to be omitted.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Just like overclocking, undervolting is highly subject to the so-called silicon lottery: one CPU can undervolt slightly better than the other and vice versa.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The *switching power* dissipated by a chip using static CMOS gates is $\alpha \cdot C\cdot V^{2}\cdot f$ , where C is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle, V is the supply voltage, f is the switching frequency, and $\alpha$ is the activity factor.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Since V is squared, this part of the power consumption decreases quadratically with voltage.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The formula is not exact however, as many modern chips are not implemented using 100% CMOS, but also use special memory circuits, dynamic logic such as domino logic, etc.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Moreover, there is also a static leakage current, which has become more and more accentuated as feature sizes have become smaller (below 90 nanometres) and threshold levels lower.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Accordingly, dynamic voltage scaling is widely used as part of strategies to manage switching power consumption in battery powered devices such as cell phones and laptop computers.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Low voltage modes are used in conjunction with lowered clock frequencies to minimize power consumption associated with components such as CPUs and DSPs; only when significant computational power is needed will the voltage and frequency be raised.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Some peripherals also support low voltage operational modes.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] For example, low power MMC and SD cards can run at 1.8 V as well as at 3.3 V, and driver stacks may conserve power by switching to the lower voltage after detecting a card which supports it.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] When leakage current is a significant factor in terms of power consumption, chips are often designed so that portions of them can be powered completely off.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] This is not usually viewed as being dynamic voltage scaling, because it is not transparent to software.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] When sections of chips can be turned off, as for example on TI OMAP3 processors, drivers and other support software need to support that.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The speed at which a digital circuit can switch states - that is, to go from "low" (VSS) to "high" (VDD) or vice versa - is proportional to the voltage differential in that circuit.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Reducing the voltage means that circuits switch slower, reducing the maximum frequency at which that circuit can run.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] This, in turn, reduces the rate at which program instructions that can be issued, which may increase run time for program segments which are sufficiently CPU-bound.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] This again highlights why dynamic voltage scaling is generally done in conjunction with dynamic frequency scaling, at least for CPUs.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] There are complex tradeoffs to consider, which depend on the particular system, the load presented to it, and power management goals.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Mobile Sensors and Context-Aware Computing), clocks and voltages might be raised together.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Otherwise, they may both be kept low to maximize battery life.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The 167-processor AsAP 2 chip enables individual processors to make extremely fast (on the order of 1-2ns) and locally controlled changes to their own supply voltages.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Processors connect their local power grid to either a higher (VddHi) or lower (VddLow) supply voltage, or can be cut off entirely from either grid to dramatically cut leakage power.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Another approach uses per-core on-chip switching regulators for dynamic voltage and frequency scaling (DVFS).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Unix system provides a userspace governor, allowing to modify the CPU frequencies (though limited to hardware capabilities).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Dynamic frequency scaling is another power conservation technique that works on the same principles as dynamic voltage scaling.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Both dynamic voltage scaling and dynamic frequency scaling can be used to prevent computer system overheating, which can result in program or operating system crashes, and possibly hardware damage.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Reducing the voltage supplied to the CPU below the manufacturer's recommended minimum setting can result in system instability.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The efficiency of some electrical components, such as voltage regulators, decreases with increasing temperature, so the power used may increase with temperature causing thermal runaway.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Increases in voltage or frequency may increase system power demands even faster than the CMOS formula indicates, and vice versa.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] The primary caveat of overvolting is increased heat: the power dissipated by a circuit increases with the square of the voltage applied, so even small voltage increases significantly affect power.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] At higher temperatures, transistor performance is adversely affected, and at some threshold, the performance reduction due to the heat exceeds the potential gains from the higher voltages.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Overheating and damage to circuits can occur very quickly when using high voltages.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] There are also longer-term concerns: various adverse device-level effects such as hot carrier injection and electromigration occur more rapidly at higher voltages, decreasing the lifespan of overvolted components.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] In order to mitigate the increased heat from overvolting, it's recommended to use liquid cooling to achieve higher ceilings and thresholds than you normally would with an aftermarket cooler.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/dynamic-voltage-scaling] Also known as 'all-in-one' (AIO) coolers, they offer a far more effective method of unit cooling by relocating heat outside a computer case via the fans on the radiator whereas air cooling only disperses heat from the affected unit, increasing overall ambient temperatures.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Gradual loss of energy from a charged capacitor is primarily caused by electronic devices attached to the capacitors, such as transistors or diodes, which conduct a small amount of current even when they are turned off.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Even though this off current is an order of magnitude less than the current through the device when it is on, the current still slowly discharges the capacitor.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Another contributor to leakage from a capacitor is from the undesired imperfection of some dielectric materials used in capacitors, also known as *dielectric leakage*.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] It is a result of the dielectric material not being a perfect insulator and having some non-zero conductivity, allowing a *leakage current* to flow, slowly discharging the capacitor.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Another type of leakage occurs when current leaks out of the intended circuit, instead flowing through some alternate path.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] This sort of leakage is undesirable because the current flowing through the alternate path can cause damage, fires, RF noise, or electrocution.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage of this type can be measured by observing that the current flow at some point in the circuit does not match the flow at another.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage in a high-voltage system can be fatal to a human in contact with the leak, as when a person accidentally grounds a high-voltage power line.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage may also mean an unwanted transfer of energy from one circuit to another.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] For example, magnetic lines of flux will not be entirely confined within the core of a power transformer; another circuit may couple to the transformer and receive some leaked energy at the frequency of the electric mains, which will cause audible hum in an audio application.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage current is also any current that flows when the ideal current is zero.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Such is the case in electronic assemblies when they are in standby, disabled, or "sleep" mode (standby power).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] These devices can draw one or two microamperes while in their quiescent state compared to hundreds or thousands of milliamperes while in full operation.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] These leakage currents are becoming a significant factor to portable device manufacturers because of their undesirable effect on battery run time for the consumer.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] The current that flows through these capacitors is due to the capacitors' impedance at power line frequencies.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Some amount of leakage current is generally considered acceptable, however excessive leakage current, exceeding 30 mA, can create a hazard for users of the equipment.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] In some applications, e.g. medical devices with patient contact, the acceptable amount of leakage current can be quite low, less than 10uA.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] In semiconductor devices, leakage is a quantum phenomenon where mobile charge carriers (electrons or holes) tunnel through an insulating region.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage increases exponentially as the thickness of the insulating region decreases.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Tunneling leakage can also occur across semiconductor junctions between heavily doped P-type and N-type semiconductors.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Other than tunneling via the gate insulator or junctions, carriers can also leak between source and drain terminals of a Metal Oxide Semiconductor (MOS) transistor.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] The primary source of leakage occurs inside transistors, but electrons can also leak between interconnects.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage increases power consumption and if sufficiently large can cause complete circuit failure.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage is currently one of the main factors limiting increased computer processor performance.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Efforts to minimize leakage include the use of strained silicon, high-κ dielectrics, and/or stronger dopant levels in the semiconductor.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage reduction to continue Moore's law will not only require new material solutions but also proper system design.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Certain types of semiconductor manufacturing defects exhibit themselves as increased leakage.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Thus measuring leakage, or Iddq testing, is a quick, inexpensive method for finding defective chips.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Increased leakage is a common failure mode resulting from non-catastrophic overstress of a semiconductor device, when the junction or the gate oxide suffers permanent damage not sufficient to cause a catastrophic failure.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Overstressing the gate oxide can lead to stress-induced leakage current.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] In bipolar junction transistors, the emitter current is the sum of the collector and base currents.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] The collector current has two components: minority carriers and majority carriers.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] The minority current is called the leakage current.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] In heterostructure field-effect transistors (HFETs) the gate leakage is usually attributed to the high density of traps residing within the barrier.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] The gate leakage of GaN HFETs has been so far observed to remain at higher levels compared with the other counterparts such as GaAs.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage current is generally measured in microamperes.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] For a reverse-biased diode it is temperature sensitive.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/leakage-electronics] Leakage current must be carefully examined for applications that work in wide temperature ranges to know the diode characteristics.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Power gating affects design architecture more than clock gating.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] It increases time delays, as power gated modes have to be safely entered and exited.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Architectural trade-offs exist between designing for the amount of leakage power saving in low power modes and the energy dissipation to enter and exit the low power modes.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Shutting down the blocks can be accomplished either by software or hardware.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Driver software can schedule the power down operations.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] A dedicated power management controller is another option.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] An externally switched power supply is a very basic form of power gating to achieve long term leakage power reduction.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] To shut off the block for small intervals of time, internal power gating is more suitable.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] CMOS switches that provide power to the circuitry are controlled by power gating controllers.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Outputs of the power gated block discharge slowly.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Hence output voltage levels spend more time in threshold voltage level.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] This can lead to larger short circuit current.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Power gating uses low-leakage PMOS transistors as header switches to shut off power supplies to parts of a design in standby or sleep mode.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] NMOS footer switches can also be used as sleep transistors.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Inserting the sleep transistors splits the chip's power network into a permanent power network connected to the power supply and a virtual power network that drives the cells and can be turned off.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Typically, high threshold voltage (Vth) sleep transistors are used for power gating in a technique sometimes known as multi-threshold CMOS (MTCMOS).
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The sleep transistor sizing is an important design parameter.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The quality of this complex power network is critical to the success of a power-gating design.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Two of the most critical parameters are the IR-drop and the penalties in silicon area and routing resources.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Power gating can be implemented using cell- or cluster-based (or fine grain) approaches or a distributed coarse-grained approach.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Power gating implementation has additional considerations for timing closure implementation.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The following parameters need to be considered and their values carefully chosen for a successful implementation of this methodology.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] *Gate control slew rate*: In power gating, this is an important parameter that determines the power gating efficiency.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] When the slew rate is small, it takes more time to switch off and switch-on the circuit and hence can affect the power gating efficiency.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Slew rate is controlled through buffering the gate control signal.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] *Simultaneous switching capacitance*: This important constraint refers to the amount of circuit that can be switched simultaneously without affecting the power network integrity.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] If a large amount of the circuit is switched simultaneously, the resulting "rush current" can compromise the power network integrity.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The circuit needs to be switched in stages in order to prevent this.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] *Power gate leakage*: Since power gates are made of active transistors, leakage reduction is an important consideration to maximize power savings.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Adding a sleep transistor to every cell that is to be turned off imposes a large area penalty, and individually gating the power of every cluster of cells creates timing issues introduced by inter-cluster voltage variation that are difficult to resolve.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Fine-grain power gating encapsulates the switching transistor as a part of the standard cell logic.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Switching transistors are designed by either the library IP vendor or standard cell designer.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Usually these cell designs conform to the normal standard cell rules and can easily be handled by EDA tools for implementation.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The size of the gate control is designed considering the worst-case scenario that will require the circuit to switch during every clock cycle, resulting in a huge area impact.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Some of the recent designs implement the fine-grain power gating selectively, but only for the low Vth cells.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] If the technology allows multiple Vth libraries, the use of low Vth devices is minimum in the design (20%), so that the area impact can be reduced.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] When using power gates on the low Vth cells the output must be isolated if the next stage is a high Vth cell.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Otherwise it can cause the neighboring high Vth cell to have leakage when output goes to an unknown state due to power gating.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Gate control slew rate constraint is achieved by having a buffer distribution tree for the control signals.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The buffers must be chosen from a set of always on buffers (buffers without the gate control signal) designed with high Vth cells.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The inherent difference between when a cell switches off with respect to another, minimizes the rush current during switch-on and switch-off.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Usually the gating transistor is designed as a high Vth device.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Coarse-grain power gating offers further flexibility by optimizing the power gating cells where there is low switching activity.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Leakage optimization has to be done at the coarse grain level, swapping the low leakage cell for the high leakage one.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Fine-grain power gating is an elegant methodology resulting in up to 10 times leakage reduction.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] This type of power reduction makes it an appealing technique if the power reduction requirement is not satisfied by multiple Vth optimization alone.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The coarse-grained approach implements the grid style sleep transistors which drives cells locally through shared virtual power networks.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] This approach is less sensitive to PVT variation, introduces less IR-drop variation, and imposes a smaller area overhead than the cell- or cluster-based implementations.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] In coarse-grain power gating, the power-gating transistor is a part of the power distribution network rather than the standard cell.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] *Column-based*: The power gates are inserted within the module with the cells abutted to each other in the form of columns.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The global power is the higher layers of metal, while the switched power is in the lower layers.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Gate sizing depends on the overall switching current of the module at any given time.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Since only a fraction of circuits switch at any point of time, power gate sizes are smaller as compared to the fine-grain switches.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Dynamic power simulation using worst-case vectors can determine the worst-case switching for the module and hence the size.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The IR drop can also be factored into the analysis.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Simultaneous switching capacitance is a major consideration in coarse-grain power gating implementation.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] In order to limit simultaneous switching, gate control buffers can be daisy chained, and special counters can be used to selectively turn on blocks of switches.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Isolation cells are used to prevent short circuit current.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] As the name suggests, these cells isolate the power gated block from the normally-on block.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Isolation cells are specially designed for low short circuit current when input is at threshold voltage level.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Isolation control signals are provided by the power gating controller.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Isolation of the signals of a switchable module is essential to preserve design integrity.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Usually a simple OR or AND logic can function as an output isolation device.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Multiple state retention schemes are available in practice to preserve the state before a module shuts down.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The simplest technique is to scan out the register values into a memory before shutting down a module.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] When the module wakes up, the values are scanned back from the memory.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] When power gating is used, the system needs some form of state retention, such as scanning out data to a RAM, then scanning it back in when the system is reawakened.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] For critical applications, the memory states must be maintained within the cell, a condition that requires a retention flop to store bits in a table.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] That makes it possible to restore the bits very quickly during wakeup.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Retention registers are special low leakage flip-flops used to hold the data of the main registers of the power gated block.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Thus the internal state of the block during power down mode can be retained and loaded back to it when the block is reactivated.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] Retention registers are always powered up.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] The retention strategy is design dependent.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-gating] A power gating controller controls the retention mechanism such as when to save the current contents of the power gating block and when to restore it back.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] The increasing speed and complexity of today’s designs implies a significant increase in the power consumption of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) chips.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] To meet this challenge, researchers have developed many different design techniques to reduce power.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] The complexity of today’s ICs, with over 100 million transistors, clocked at over 1 GHz, means manual power optimization would be hopelessly slow and all too likely to contain errors.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Computer-aided design (CAD) tools and methodologies are mandatory.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] One of the key features that led to the success of complementary metal-oxide semiconductor, or CMOS, technology was its intrinsic low-power consumption.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] This meant that circuit designers and electronic design automation (EDA) tools could afford to concentrate on maximizing circuit performance and minimizing circuit area.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Another interesting feature of CMOS technology is its nice scaling properties, which has permitted a steady decrease in the feature size (see Moore's law), allowing for more and more complex systems on a single chip, working at higher clock frequencies.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Power consumption concerns came into play with the appearance of the first portable electronic systems in the late 1980s.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] In this market, battery lifetime is a decisive factor for the commercial success of the product.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Another fact that became apparent at about the same time was that the increasing integration of more active elements per die area would lead to prohibitively large-energy consumption of an integrated circuit.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] A high absolute level of power is not only undesirable for economic and environmental reasons, but it also creates the problem of heat dissipation.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] In order to keep the device working at acceptable temperature levels, excessive heat may require expensive heat removal systems.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] These factors have contributed to the rise of power as a major design parameter on par with performance and die size.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] In fact, power consumption is regarded as the limiting factor in the continuing scaling of CMOS technology.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] To respond to this challenge, in the last decade or so, intensive research has been put into developing computed-aided design (CAD) tools that address the problem of power optimization.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Initial efforts were directed to circuit and logic-level tools because at this level CAD tools were more mature and there was a better handle on the issues.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Today, most of the research for CAD tools targets system or architectural level optimization, which potentially have a higher overall impact, given the breadth of their application.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Together with optimization tools, efficient techniques for power estimation are required, both as an absolute indicator that the circuit’s consumption meets some target value and as a relative indicator of the power merits of different alternatives during design space exploration.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Power can be estimated at a number of levels of detail.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] The higher levels of abstraction are faster and handle larger circuits, but are less accurate.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Many different techniques are used to reduce power consumption at the circuit level.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Logic synthesis can also be optimized in many ways to keep power consumption under control.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] There are file formats that can be used to write design files specifying the Power intent and implementation of a design.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] The information in these files allow the EDA tools to automatically insert power control features and to check that the result matches the intent.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] The IEEE DASC provides a home for developing this format in the form of the IEEE P1801 working group.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] During 2006 and the first two months of 2007, both Unified Power Format and Common Power Format were developed to support various tools.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] The IEEE P1801 working groups operates with the goal of providing for convergence of these two standards.
[src:power-analysis-vlsi/power-optimization-eda] Several EDA tools have been developed for supporting architectural level power estimation including McPAT, Wattch, and Simplepower.
